# Docsify Research & Best Practices Guide

> **Date**: 2026-01-14
> **Purpose**: Reusable knowledge base for setting up high-quality documentation sites with Docsify.

---

## 1. Core Philosophy: Why Docsify?

Unlike Docusaurus, Jekyll, or Hugo, **Docsify generates your documentation website on the fly at runtime**. 

*   **No Build Step**: There is no static HTML generation step. You ship raw markdown files.
*   **Client-Side Rendering**: A smart router fetches markdown files and renders them as HTML in the browser.
*   **Simple Hosting**: Can be hosted on GitHub Pages, GitLab Pages, or any static web server (NGINX, Apache, Python http.server) without complex CI/CD build pipelines.

---

## 2. Essential Configuration (`window.$docsify`)

The core configuration lives in `index.html`. Here are the high-value settings for a professional UX:

| Setting | Value | Purpose |
|---------|-------|---------|
| `loadSidebar` | `true` | UI: Enables a custom `_sidebar.md` for navigation control. |
| `nameLink` | `'/'` | UX: Ensures the logo/title always links back to home. |
| `subMaxLevel` | `2` or `3` | UX: Generates an automatic Table of Contents (TOC) for the current page in the sidebar. |
| `auto2top` | `true` | UX: Automatic scroll-to-top when navigating between pages (critical for long pages). |
| `repo` | `'https://...'` | Community: Adds a "GitHub" corner widge linking to the source code. |
| `routerMode` | `'hash'` | Default. Use `'history'` only if you have server-side rewrite rules configured. |

---

## 3. Top Tier Plugins Ecosystem

A refined list of plugins that bring "pro" features to Docsify:

### Navigation & UX
*   **[docsify-sidebar-collapse](https://github.com/i-akame/docsify-sidebar-collapse)**:
    *   *Why*: Essential for large documentation sets. Collapses sidebar groups to reduce clutter.
    *   *Usage*: Include script + css. `sidebarDisplayLevel: 1` in config to start collapsed.
*   **[docsify-pagination](https://github.com/imyelo/docsify-pagination)**:
    *   *Why*: Adds "Previous / Next" buttons at the bottom of pages. Creates a linear reading flow.

### Content Enhancement
*   **[docsify-copy-code](https://github.com/jperasmus/docsify-copy-code)**:
    *   *Why*: Adds a one-click "Copy" button to every code block. Mandatory for tech docs.
*   **[docsify-tabs](https://jhildenbiddle.github.io/docsify-tabs)**:
    *   *Why*: Render tabbed content (e.g., "NPM" vs "Yarn" installation) using markdown comments.
*   **[docsify-plugin-flexible-alerts](https://github.com/fzankl/docsify-plugin-flexible-alerts)**:
    *   *Why*: Replaces blockquotes (`>`) with styled alerts (Note, Warning, Danger). Matches Docusaurus/GitHub admonition style.

### Visuals
*   **[docsify-mermaid](https://github.com/docsifyjs/docsify-mermaid)**:
    *   *Why*: Renders Mermaid diagrams direct from markdown code blocks.
*   **[Zoom Image](https://docsify.js.org/#/plugins?id=zoom-image)**:
    *   *Why*: Native plugin (just add script) to allow medium-style image zooming on click.

---

## 4. Theming Strategy

### Recommended Theme: Docsify Darklight
*   **[docsify-darklight-theme](https://github.com/boopathikumar/docsify-darklight-theme)**
*   **Pros**: 
    *   Built-in Dark/Light mode toggle (saved to local storage).
    *   Clean, modern typography (Inter font).
    *   Good contrast ratios.
*   **Customization**: Override CSS variables in the `<style>` block:
    ```css
    :root {
      --docsifyThemeColor: #3B82F6; /* Your Brand Color */
      --docsifyDarklightThemeColor: #3B82F6;
    }
    ```

### Alternative: Docsify Themeable
*   Uses a CSS variable system for granular control but requires more initial setup.

---

## 5. Deployment Guide

Since there is no build step, deployment is trivial.

### Local Development
```bash
# Python (pre-installed)
python3 -m http.server 3000

# or Node.js
npx docsify-cli serve .
```

### GitHub Pages
1.  Enable GitHub Pages in repo settings.
2.  Point source to `/docs` folder (or root `/` if repo is docs-only).
3.  Done. No GitHub Actions needed.

### NGINX / Docker
Serve as static files. Ensure `404` pages redirect to `index.html` (or separate 404.md file) if using History mode.

